<div id="banner">
	<h1>Nader for Geeks</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>Dave Winer is <a href="http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/2003/11/17#a651">asking the candidates who&#8217;ve adopted blogs for fundraising to promise to keep the Internet free</a>. No one&#8217;s biting. Larry Lessig has invited candidates to speak on his blog, only to get the most mealy-mouthed responses on his favorite issues. Let&#8217;s look at Nader&#8217;s record:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.cptech.org/ms/">Fought the Microsoft monopoly</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.cptech.org/ecom/icann/">Fought the ICANN monster</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.cptech.org/ecom/gp.html">Asked the government to consider procuring free software</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.cptech.org/ip/health/">Fought for compulsory drug patent licenses when needed</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/11.03/view.html?pg=3">Fought software patents</a>.</li>
<li>Fought business method patents.</li>
<li>Fought for strong open access/end-to-end protection of the Internet.</li>
<li>Fought bilateral intellectual monopoly treaties.</li>
<li>Fought for low-power FM.</li>
<li>Fought for public domain information resources.</li>
<li>Fought for Internet privacy protection.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.nader.org/interest/053103.html"><em>Long</em> fought for true media diversity</a>.</li>
</ul>

<p>He did this all before it was popular. He did this without being pushed to do it by campaign contributors. He did it because it was right. I don&#8217;t want to sound all hippy-dippy here, but maybe this is a guy we should support.</p>

<p class="posted">posted November 19, 2003 07:48 AM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_politics">Politics</a>)  <a href="001077" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

